There is a clear distinction to be drawn between the absolutely necessary process of setting priorities for health care and that involved in the provision of care by an individual doctor for an individual patient. This dilemma faces the Colleges as well as each doctor but, while we play our part in helping the politicians to tease out the priorities of health care need, neither the Colleges nor individual physicians wish to be seen to be part of a rationing process in which some treatments are denied because of lack of funds;

 that is something which society has to decide through government and their representatives in management

. This poses a particular difficulty for those physicians who take on the dual role of clinician and manager and thus have to participate on behalf of the Health Service in decisions about the distribution of scarce resources. We must ensure that these roles are clearly distinguished and the two modes of behaviourâ€”both importantâ€”are not confused. The implications of not doing so are bad for doctors and bad for patients.

